<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900406-0103</DOCNO><DOCID>900406-0103.</DOCID><HL>   Home National Corp.   Says Principal Unit   May Get a Receiver</HL><DATE>04/06/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8A</SO><CO>   HNCP</CO><IN>BANKS (BNK)</IN><LP>   MILFORD, Mass. -- Home National Corp. said regulators mayappoint a receiver for its principal unit, Home National Bankof Milford. The move is possible because it is &quot;verydoubtful&quot; the unit can raise $8 million to pad its $22.1million loan loss reserves, as advised by regulators after anexamination of the bank.   The company warned that failure to raise capital couldcause the Comptroller of the Currency and other regulatoryauthorities to &quot;take such action as they considerappropriate, including the possible appointment of a receiverfor the institution.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Home National also said it expects to report operatinglosses for the first quarter. In the year-ago period, thebank holding company had a loss of $3 million, or 47 cents ashare.   The operating losses and the increase in the loan lossreserves will result in a deficit of shareholder equity ofnot less than $6 million, the company said.   In addition, Home National said it may restate its 1989year-end results, which were already revised last month toshow a loss of $26.6 million, or $4.18 a share, compared withprofit of $4.1 million, or 62 cents a share, in 1988.   Home National Corp. had assets of $484.5 million at Dec.31.</TEXT></DOC>